pr_title: [WIP]Make a common template for /api pages
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This PR removes the need for multiple `.md` files and makes a common template to generate /api pages from the OpenAPI data. This is currently a WIP.
**Work plan:**
- [x] Add title of API pages as `summary` parameter in YAML.
- [x] Write MarkdownProcessor to get title from `summary` parameter.
- [x] Refactor titles of existing /api files to use markdowngenerator.
- [x] Fix HTML titles for the /api pages.
- [x] Add the template `.md` file.
- [x] Refactor code to use the template `.md` file.  
- [x] Remove files following the template(CHECKED VIA SCRIPT)
- [x] Proper rendering of JS examples.
- [x] Proper rendering of 404 responses.
- [x] Tackle specific `curl` options
- [x] Tackle specific configurations(like admin).
- [x] Migrate stray descriptions.

**Testing plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->


**GIFs or screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html
  -->

pr_title: [WIP]Make a common template for /api pages
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This PR removes the need for multiple `.md` files and makes a common template to generate /api pages from the OpenAPI data. This is currently a WIP.
**Work plan:**
- [x] Add title of API pages as `summary` parameter in YAML.

pr_title: [WIP]Make a common template for /api pages
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This PR removes the need for multiple `.md` files and makes a common template to generate /api pages from the OpenAPI data. This is currently a WIP.
**Work plan:**
- [x] Add title of API pages as `summary` parameter in YAML.
- [x] Write MarkdownProcessor to get title from `summary` parameter.
- [x] Refactor titles of existing /api files to use markdowngenerator.
- [x] Fix HTML titles for the /api pages.
- [x] Add the template `.md` file.
- [x] Refactor code to use the template `.md` file.  
- [x] Remove files following the template(CHECKED VIA SCRIPT)
- [x] Proper rendering of JS examples.
- [x] Proper rendering of 404 responses.
- [x] Tackle specific `curl` options
- [x] Tackle specific configurations(like admin).
- [x] Migrate stray descriptions.

**Testing plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->


**GIFs or screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html

(Since we may be trying to auto-generate `rest-endpoints.md` in the future, too)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 27, 0, 52, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 640689311, 'comment_body': 'This is later used in the code as well. Quoting from there:
```
# The following is a somewhat hacky approach to extract titles from articles.
        # Hack: `context["article"] has a leading `/`, so we use + to add directories.
        article_path = os.path.join(settings.DEPLOY_ROOT, "templates") + context["article"]
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 27, 14, 39, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 641056994, 'comment_body': 'I see, OK; worth doing a comment then, because generally one should use the preferred combination functions.

(Maybe we want `urljoin` instead?)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 27, 23, 57, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 641838938, 'comment_body': "Made the /api/ consistent.

Also, modified the logic at places so that `/api/invalid` doesn't crash anymore.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 28, 22, 20, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 641839367, 'comment_body': 'I thought about it, but if we use the client to get the actual raw HTML, then there is no way of distinguishing sidebar links and the main rest-endpoints links. Distinguishing the two kinds of links might make the code messy.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 28, 22, 22, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 641840568, 'comment_body': "`urljoin` can only join two at a time, so anyway we would have to use multiple instances of it or combine it with `path.join`. Idts it's as clean a solution as we would expect.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 28, 22, 26, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 642540739, 'comment_body': 'I realised that we need to(and we are) test those as well. Changed the code to use the HTML page for parsing links.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 31, 14, 48, 14, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 644380778, 'comment_body': 'Can we pull this description from a common entry rather than having N copies of it?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 2, 23, 22, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 644382213, 'comment_body': "This calling convention is really messy.  Rather than returning N variables, can you define a `@dataclass` for the return value of `self.get_path` in a prep commit (with no functional changes) with the `sidebar_index` and `http_status` fields, and then later commits can extend that object?  

I'm also not sure we need to modify `get_path` in the /help/ code path at all; could we instead just have the /api/ code be in a function only present on that subclass?  ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 2, 23, 26, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 644382586, 'comment_body': "Can you pull this commit as well as a targeted bug fix for /api/invalid being broken in master into a smaller prep PR that we can merge now?  We're getting 500s in chat.zulip.org from crawlers right now, and I'd like to be able to merge a fix for that (with this test code) tomorrow even if the rest needs more round trips.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 2, 23, 27, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 644383029, 'comment_body': 'Why the change to use the `../../` stuff?  We previously were having paths starting from the CWD, which should be correct and save.  

More generally, this commit is extremely hard to read because it makes N different types of changes all at once.

It might be helpful to do a separate preparatory refactor PR for this file with much smaller commits.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 2, 23, 29, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 644383681, 'comment_body': 'Can you add a comment explaining the purpose of this case?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 2, 23, 31, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 644384128, 'comment_body': 'I think this block may need to be in the next commit, to avoid double-including this content.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 2, 23, 32, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 645452685, 'comment_body': '@timabbott Indeed this breaks without the second commit. I had split it for easier review in this case.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 4, 10, 5, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 645453654, 'comment_body': 'The usefulness of this comes in the form that we can add the lines to generate JS examples whether that particular endpoint actually has JS examples or not. Thus, it would expand coverage of the template. Maybe I should split this into a different commit to make the purpose more clear?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 4, 10, 6, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 645454238, 'comment_body': "That is what I was gonna do in the next commit :)(along with fixing the cases where the script didn't find any descriptions).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 4, 10, 7, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 645524815, 'comment_body': '@timabbott opened https://github.com/zulip/zulip/pull/18696 for this commit instead.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 4, 12, 18, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 645531428, 'comment_body': "Changed  to use the dataclass.

Splitting the two functions would've duplicated a lot of code IMO, since the endpoint_name and endpoin_method are coming as a by-product of checking the http_status for the endpoint(to differentiate between an invalid endpoint where we return 404, or a valid endpoint whose file got deleted, in case we return 200).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 4, 12, 29, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 645716737, 'comment_body': 'Yeah, seems wise.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 4, 16, 51, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 645724648, 'comment_body': "@timabbott Hmmm I'll split these further. The remaining would still need some work as of now.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 4, 17, 3, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 656666726, 'comment_body': 'This is very weird code; you should write `article_path = self.get_path(article)`, and mypy should infer the type.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 0, 21, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657243298, 'comment_body': '@timabbott Changed the code to the other format.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 15, 51, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657516774, 'comment_body': "I think we don't want this heading along, since it's a duplicate.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 23, 6, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657517871, 'comment_body': 'I don't understand this logic; shouldn't it just be `if doc_name != "/events:get" / else` , so that every endpoint but `events:get` has the default logic?

(I think also a cleaner way to write it would be to have `if doc_name == "/events:get": / else` block.)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 23, 9, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657518385, 'comment_body': "Do we consider it a bug to have any endpoint without a Python code example? ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 23, 16, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657521479, 'comment_body': 'I kinda feel like this name isn't quite right; maybe we want:
```
class DocumentationArticle:
    article_path: str
    article_http_status: int
    endpoint_path: Optional[str]  # should be `None` rather than `""` if not a REST API page?
    endpoint_method: Optional[str]  # should be `None` rather than `""` if not a REST API page?
```

(I think `endpoint_path`, since `endpoint_name` would be the `operationId`, not the thing with `/`s in it).', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 23, 20, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657548294, 'comment_body': "Currently, the two fetch-api-keys endpoints don't have python examples -- hence the empty string.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 0, 43, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657647031, 'comment_body': 'Modified the code.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 5, 56, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657722630, 'comment_body': 'Changed the naming.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 8, 7, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657722771, 'comment_body': 'Changed the naming.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 8, 7, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 657723242, 'comment_body': 'This already got merged with the changed description :)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 24, 8, 8, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 658148110, 'comment_body': 'OK, cool. pr_title: apidocs: Migrate admin_config out of templates.
pr_body:
Currently, the `admin_config` configuration was
hardcoded in the templates, but as a goal of creating
a common template, we need to move all configurations
outside.

Moved the checking for function and language which need
admin_config out of templates into the code.

[{'comment_id': 650320253, 'comment_body': 'I think structurally, whether an endpoint requires an organization administrator to use it will be a property of the endpoint, and thus should probably live in the OpenAPI files.  This is an OK intermediate state, but maybe we should take the opportunity to add an `x-requires-administrator` tag using https://swagger.io/docs/specification/openapi-extensions/?

We will likely also want to have that flag control whether to show a "requires organization administrator" banner at the top of the page like we do in many Help Center articles.

', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 12, 0, 29, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 652769513, 'comment_body': "Let's call this `x-requires-administrator: true`; I don't think `admin-config` is going to read particularly intuitively.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 16, 14, 52, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 652770419, 'comment_body': "This ends up on its own line because it's a list, right?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 16, 14, 53, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 652771496, 'comment_body': '`check_requires_administrator` would be a better name for this.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 16, 14, 54, 11, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 652774293, 'comment_body': 'Indeed -- the list contains each line that is supposed to be present( as can be seen in `title.extend(raw_title.splitlines())`)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 16, 14, 57, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: curl_examples: Migrate exclude and include config.
pr_body:
Currently, the include and exclude configurations
were hardoded in the templates, but as a part
of moving towards a common template, we need
to move all configurations out of the templates.

Added a dictionary to store parameters for include
and exclude, and modified the logic to add include
and exclude from dictionaries to the ones hardcoded
in template, which are useful if there are different
variants of include and exclude present, with the base
one in the dictionary, and the variants being added
in the dictionary.

<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->


**Testing plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->


**GIFs or screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html
  -->

If not, we should remove them from the signature.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 16, 15, 0, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 652779941, 'comment_body': "I think the previous model with these parameters being Optional (with None / not sent meaning that the behavior was not requested) makes more sense to me, especially since the empty list for `include` at least means something (don't include anything).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 16, 15, 3, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 652780608, 'comment_body': '@timabbott  These do get called in cases where there are multiple configurations possible. So, I have kept the ones in the dictionaries as a base for the endpoints, and additional ones can be added by hardcoding in templates.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 16, 15, 3, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 652781297, 'comment_body': 'For instance,

To subscribe another user to a stream, you may pass in

pr_title: [WIP]Make a common template for /api pages
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This PR removes the need for multiple `.md` files and makes a common template to generate /api pages from the OpenAPI data. This is currently a WIP.
**Work plan:**
- [x] Add title of API pages as `summary` parameter in YAML.
- [x] Write MarkdownProcessor to get title from `summary` parameter.
- [x] Refactor titles of existing /api files to use markdowngenerator.
- [x] Fix HTML titles for the /api pages.
- [x] Add the template `.md` file.
- [x] Refactor code to use the template `.md` file.  
- [x] Remove files following the template(CHECKED VIA SCRIPT)
- [x] Proper rendering of JS examples.
- [x] Proper rendering of 404 responses.
- [x] Tackle specific `curl` options
- [x] Tackle specific configurations(like admin).
- [x] Migrate stray descriptions.

**Testing plan:** <!-- How have you tested? -->


**GIFs or screenshots:** <!-- If a UI change.  See:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorials/screenshot-and-gif-software.html
  -->


<!-- Also be sure to make clear, coherent commits:
  https://zulip.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing/version-control.html
  -->

', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 23, 21, 13, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 637602068, 'comment_body': 'We probably want to keep this as `-`s for consistency.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 23, 21, 14, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 637602199, 'comment_body': "I'd call these local variables `endpoint` and `method`; no need for the `each_` prefix.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 23, 21, 15, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 637602298, 'comment_body': 'It might be cleaner to do `operationId = openapi_spec.openapi()["paths"][endpoint][method].get("operationId")`

and then just compare that value.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 23, 21, 16, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 637602377, 'comment_body': "I'd recommend returning a tuple, rather than a `:`-delimited string that the caller needs to parse.

Should we throw an AssertionError if we didn't find it?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 23, 21, 17, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 637602538, 'comment_body': 'Possibly just `Get public temporary URL` in an "Files" section makes the most sense.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 23, 21, 18, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 638368896, 'comment_body': 'That was a slight overlook on my part. Fixed.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 25, 0, 14, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 638368994, 'comment_body': 'Changed to "Outgoing webhooks" :)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 25, 0, 14, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 638369154, 'comment_body': 'It was indeed a misleading name. I was going to replace all `_` by `-` in this file, but forgot before pushing.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 25, 0, 15, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 638890479, 'comment_body': 'Changed it to tuple. Also, AssertionError makes sense in such case -- added that', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 25, 15, 11, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 640210004, 'comment_body': 'I think you probably want to be consistent about whether `/api/` is required here.

Also this logic (and others) crash when you visit `/api/invalid`.  So I think that the `zerver/views/documentation.py` logic which decides whether to render the "404 error page" needs to be doing this parsing, not this code, since otherwise it's possible to reach the AssertionError in `get_endpoint_from_operationid`.

Ideally, we do it in one place, but it's not the end of the world to do it twice.  That said, if we are doing it in more than one place, we should have a function rather than copying this in N places.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 27, 0, 43, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 640210113, 'comment_body': 'Why is path added rather than included in the `os.path.join`?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 27, 0, 43, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 640214447, 'comment_body': 'I think we want to do just do a `client_get` to fetch the actual HTML page, and parse the links on the page.  

(Since we may be trying to auto-generate `rest-endpoints.md` in the future, too)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 27, 0, 52, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 640689311, 'comment_body': 'This is later used in the code as well. Quoting from there:
```

        # Hack: `context["article"] has a leading `/`, so we use + to add directories.
        article_path = os.path.join(settings.DEPLOY_ROOT, "templates") + context["article"]

pr_title: docs: Document the new APIDocs template system.
pr_body:
Recently, the need for individual Markdown templates for
every endpoint's OpenAPI page was removed, as they are now
auto-generated from OpenAPI data. Further, as a part of this
migration, several new fields and Markdown extensions were added.
This commit updates the documentation to reflect the changes that
have occured as a result of the migration.

pr_title: openapi: Make endpoint operationId dash-separated.
pr_body:
The operationId is directly used in URLs of API doc pages
to find the OpenAPI data to render. However, this is dash-
separated in the URLs, and having underscore_separated IDs
in OpenAPI data doesn't allow direct comparison of the two.

This commit changes all OperationIDs from underscore_separated
to dash-separated.

pr_title: [WIP]Make a common template for /api pages
pr_body:
<!-- What's this PR for?  (Just a link to an issue is fine.) -->
This PR removes the need for multiple `.md` files and makes a common template to generate /api pages from the OpenAPI data. This is currently a WIP.
**Work plan:**
- [x] Add title of API pages as `summary` parameter in YAML.
- [x] Write MarkdownProcessor to get title from `summary` parameter.
- [x] Refactor titles of existing /api files to use markdowngenerator.
- [x] Fix HTML titles for the /api pages.
- [x] Add the template `.md` file.
- [x] Refactor code to use the template `.md` file.  
- [x] Remove files following the template(CHECKED VIA SCRIPT)
- [x] Proper rendering of JS examples.
- [x] Proper rendering of 404 responses.
- [x] Tackle specific `curl` options
- [x] Tackle specific configurations(like admin).
- [x] Migrate stray descriptions.

(Maybe we want `urljoin` instead?)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 27, 23, 57, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 641838938, 'comment_body': "Made the /api/ consistent.

I'm also not sure we need to modify `get_path` in the /help/ code path at all; could we instead just have the /api/ code be in a function only present on that subclass?  ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 2, 23, 26, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 644382586, 'comment_body': "Can you pull this commit as well as a targeted bug fix for /api/invalid being broken in master into a smaller prep PR that we can merge now? pr_title: openapi: Render all responses of an operation.
pr_body:
The current system requires specifying all the status
codes that we want to render along with the operation,
but the primary use case just needs the responses of
all the status codes, and not just one.

This commit modifies the Markdown extesnion to render
all the responses of all status codes of a specified
operation.

pr_title: openapi: Make base class for Markdown Preprocessors.
pr_body:
Most of the Markdown Preprocessors followed a common
template, and it was redundant to `run` and `init` code
multiple times for execution of the Preprocessor.

This commit adds a base class from which the preprocessors
following the pattern can inherit, and can override the
`render` function to execute the code.

pr_title: wip: Prototype mark-as-unread.
pr_body: This isn't ready for review yet, but it's probably enough for mobile/ZT to get an idea of the direction the webapp is going in.
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 648606174, 'comment_body': 'We probably want to have the code path for "receive an mark-as-unread" in a separate commit from the UI to mark messages as unread, since we'll be able to merge that as soon as we've finalized the API without finalizing UI decisions.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 19, 16, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 648628354, 'comment_body': "Yeah, I'm not even close to splitting up commits until some of the UI decisions get settled.  My basic plan is this:

* handle (theoretical) incoming events
* add one single way to un-read messages
* add next way
* add next way
* add way to resume reading

But it's still in flux.

The one clear commit to break out is the backend changes.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 19, 47, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'showell', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 648653695, 'comment_body': 'I guess the `get_inactive_recipient_ids` part looks at deactivated streams; I think this is a reminder that we may want to adjust the "mark messages as unread" backend endpoint to skip message IDs that structurally should never be marked as unread (e.g. those sent by muted users or sent to deactivated streams), since those are states we don't want to have exist.

@abhijeetbodas2001 FYI for the muting question.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 20, 15, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 648682733, 'comment_body': 'I agree.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 9, 21, 2, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'showell', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 649118107, 'comment_body': 'If we're going to allow users to mark a **particular** message or particular set of messages as unread, I think we should not treat muted sender messages specially.

If we're implementing a wider option (which I think we are in V1?) like "mark topic as unread" or "mark all messages below this message as unread", I think we should have the muted messages retain their state (remain as `read`, that is) ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 10, 12, 4, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'abhijeetbodas2001', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 649436272, 'comment_body': 'Yeah, that sounds right to me.  ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 10, 18, 44, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}]

[{'comment_id': 601173277, 'comment_body': 'This is super hacky -- `reactivation_flag` should be a bool if we were going to do this, but we have tried hard to keep per-endpoint code out of this function, and I'd like to avoid regressing that. E.g. ``` diff --git a/zerver/openapi/test_curl_examples.py b/zerver/openapi/test_curl_examples.py index ba4f431fe1..72a0f9b43e 100644 --- a/zerver/openapi/test_curl_examples.py +++ b/zerver/openapi/test_curl_examples.py @@ -49,14 +49,20 @@ def test_generated_curl_examples_for_success(client: Client, owner_client: Clien curl_command_html = md_engine.convert(line.strip()) unescaped_html = html.unescape(curl_command_html) curl_command_text = unescaped_html[len("

curl\n") : -len("

")] - - reactivation_flag = 0 - user_id = 0 curl_command_text = curl_command_text.replace( "BOT_EMAIL_ADDRESS:BOT_API_KEY", authentication_line ) + + # TODO: This needs_reactivation block is a hack. + # However, it's awkward to test the "deactivate + # myself" endpoint with how this system tries to use + # the same account for all tests without some special + # logic for that endpoint; and the hack is better than + # just not documenting the endpoint. + needs_reactivation = False + user_id = 0 if file_name == "templates/zerver/api/deactivate-own-user.md": - reactivation_flag = 1 + needs_reactivation = True user_id = client.get_profile()["user_id"] print("Testing {} ...".format(curl_command_text.split("\n")[0])) @@ -74,7 +80,7 @@ def test_generated_curl_examples_for_success(client: Client, owner_client: Clien ) response = json.loads(response_json) assert response["result"] == "success" - if reactivation_flag: + if needs_reactivation: owner_client.reactivate_user_by_id(user_id) except (AssertionError, Exception): error_template = """ ``` The right approach is to define something like the existing one for deactivating a user: ``` @openapi_param_value_generator(["/users/{user_id}:delete"]) def deactivate_user() -> Dict[str, object]: user_profile = do_create_user( email="testuser@zulip.com", password=None, full_name="test_user", realm=get_realm("zulip"), acting_user=None, ) return {"user_id": user_profile.id} ``` Namely, we should just create a new user and then have that user deactivate itself, if we can make that work. Hmm, except that's not going to work easily without more refactoring, because this test framework doesn't support using a different user account. OK, I think I'm on board with leaving the work of trying to do something better here for a follow-up issue -- can you open a follow-up issue to track the need to replace this with something less hacky?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 3, 25, 8, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}]

It sorta looks like you're trying to determine the API state by looking at whether the description starts with `foo:`, which 
I'm not sure is a pattern that makes sense to use.  Instead, we should be looking at some OpenAPI feature around the type, not text in the description.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 2, 4, 1, 38, 54, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 569882467, 'comment_body': 'Is this function the same as the one you wrote for the request parameters?  If not, why not; and if so, can we just import the function here?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 2, 4, 1, 39, 35, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 569945421, 'comment_body': "@timabbott This logic is trying to extract the name of the ```additionalProperties``` from the description, as they don't have their variable names separately, but included in description, like 
```
 additionalProperties:
                          description: |
                            `{email_id}`: A list of the names of streams that
                            the user was subscribed to as a result of the query.
                          type: array
                          items:
                            type: string
```
For the other types of variables, the name is directly available in the ```return_value``` variable.
This is being done to follow the uniform pattern of <var_name>: <data_type> <var_description> for all type of variables.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 2, 4, 4, 52, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 569962834, 'comment_body': '@timabbott It was the same function;modified the code to import the function and use it.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 2, 4, 5, 50, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 569967716, 'comment_body': "OpenAPI also renders it with description, so I'm not sure if there is some OpenAPI feature for it.

pr_title: middleware: Add client version to log and other logging improvements.
pr_body:
The first commit uses get_client_name in LogRequests's process_request and removes its usage in process_client.
The second commit adds request.client_version to LogRequest's process_request.
The third commit changes write_log_line so that it now shows client version if available.
The fourth commit uses client id instead of client name for logging.

Fixes #14067 .
[This is the cleaned up version of #14139]

update_message variant events and refactored to replace Dict with

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 628954973, 'comment_body': 'Why total=False here?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 9, 22, 59, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 628954974, 'comment_body': 'This is kinda giant; I wonder if there's a good way to define simpler classes; e.g. have the common elements in a base class, and then subclasses for "has topic edit"?  Not sure; in any case, it's an improvement to just have a defined type even if it is giant.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 9, 22, 59, 2, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 628955012, 'comment_body': "Also, ideally we'd use the class in `zerver/tornado_event_queue.py` if possible.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 9, 22, 59, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'timabbott', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 628956490, 'comment_body': 'That is something I used as a temporary solution and need to fix(hence the current WIP status). Removing it causes error since `message_ids`, which is a compulary field is calculated much later in the code and the event TypedDict is created much before. ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 9, 23, 12, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 628956870, 'comment_body': '> This is kinda giant; I wonder if there's a good way to define simpler classes; e.g. have the common elements in a base class, and then subclasses for "has topic edit"? Not sure; in any case, it's an improvement to just have a defined type even if it is giant.

I initially tried to do it this way -- but there are total 4 branching `ifs` - if there is content, if it is a stream message, if the topic is changed or stream is moved, if the topic is changed - giving rise to 16 possible classes. That *might* make the class structure, as well as the code to use the appropriate class for the TypedDict a little cluttered in my opinion.
Also, in TypedDict, it is not possible to change type of an inherited parameter in the child class, so an approach where we have Optional elements made non-optional in child classes won't work out as well.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 9, 23, 15, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 629405009, 'comment_body': "@timabbott Something that I now remembered -- the `total=False` is necessary because we need to omit the Optional parameters completely rather than including them with `None`, since the API expects those keys to be absent rather than present with value `None`, and gives error in such cases. 
A downside of doing this is that we won't be able to check for missing parameters in the event.(I followed the example of `DeleteMessagesEvent` to use `total=False`)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 10, 14, 24, 48, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 631973008, 'comment_body': '@timabbott Would this large number of different classes be desirable? Since this is the only way I think we could remove the `total=False` if that is desired.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 5, 13, 17, 20, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'MSurfer20', 'type': 'User'}]
